{{short description|The study of past tropical cyclone activity using geological proxies and historical documents}}
{{redirect|Tempestology|the generalized study of storms|Meteorology|the origins of storms and tropical cyclones|Cyclogenesis|and|Tornadogenesis}}
{{Paleontology}}
'''Paleotempestology''' is the study of past [[tropical cyclone]] activity by means of geological proxies as well as historical documentary records. The term was coined by [[Kerry Emanuel]].

==Methods==

===Sedimentary proxy records===
Examples of proxies include [[overwash]] deposits preserved in the [[sediment]]s of coastal lakes and [[marsh]]es, [[Micropaleontology|microfossil]]s such as [[foraminifera]], [[pollen]], [[diatom]]s, [[dinoflagellate]]s, [[phytolith]]s contained in coastal sediments, wave-generated or flood-generated sedimentary structures or deposits (called [[tempestite]]s) in marine or [[lagoon]]al sediments, storm wave deposited [[coral]] shingle, shell, sand and shell and pure sand shore parallel ridges.

The method of using overwash deposits preserved in coastal lake and marsh sediments is adopted from earlier studies of paleotsunami deposits. Both [[storm]]s and [[tsunami]]s leave very similar if not identical sedimentary deposits in coastal lakes and marshes and differentiating between the two in a sedimentary record can be difficult. The first studies to examine prehistoric records of tropical cyclones occurred in Australia and the South Pacific during the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref name="Baines1976">
{{cite journal |last=Baines |first=G. B. K. |authorlink= |author2=McLean, R. F. |year=1976 |title=Sequential studies of hurricane deposit evolution at Funafuti Atoll |journal=Marine Geology |volume=21 |issue= |pages=M1–M8 |id= |url= |accessdate= |quote= |doi=10.1016/0025-3227(76)90097-9 |bibcode=1976MGeol..21M...1B}}
</ref><ref name="Rhodes1980">
{{cite journal |last=Rhodes |first=E. G. |authorlink= |author2=Polach, H. A. |author3=Thom, B. G. |author4= Wilson, S. R.  |year=1980 |title=Age structure of Holocene coastal sediments, Gulf of Carpentaria, Australia |journal=Radiocarbon |volume=22 |issue= |pages=718&ndash;727 |id= |url= |accessdate= |quote= }}
</ref><ref name="Chappell1983">
{{cite journal |last=Chappell |first=J. |authorlink= |author2=Chivas, A |author3=Rhodes, E. |author4= Wallensky, E.  |year=1983 |title=Holocene palaeo-environmental changes, central to north Great Barrier Reef inner zone |journal=BMR Journal of Australian Geology and Geophysics |volume=8 |issue= |pages=223–235 |id= |url= |accessdate= |quote= }}
</ref> These studies examined multiple shore parallel ridges of coral shingle or sand and marine shells. As many as 50 ridges can be deposited at a site with each representing a past severe [[tropical cyclone]] over the previous 6,000 years. Tsunamis are not known to deposit multiple sedimentary ridges and therefore these features can be more easily attributed to a past storm at any given site.

Coastal sedimentary analyses have been done at the [[Gulf of Mexico|U.S. Gulf coast]],<ref name="Liu1999">
{{cite conference |first=Kam-biu |last=Liu |title=Millennial-scale variability in catastrophic hurricane landfalls along the Gulf of Mexico coast |conference=23d Conf. on Hurricanes and Tropical Meteorology |publisher=Amer. Meteor. Soc. |year=1999 |location=Dallas, TX |url= |pages=374–377 |id= }}
</ref><ref name="LiuFearn2000">
